In our text it is plain that the writer supposes the meeting-place mentioned to be open to non-Christians: sti-angers might enter it either from curiosity, or from sympathy, or from malice to spy out what was going on. St. Paul refers to such visits from strangers 111 1 Cor. xiv. 23. But as it is called συναγωγὴν ὑ μ ὣ ν, it is evidently assumed that it was mainly under Christian direction. The precise circumstances would of course vary from town to town.
